questions.text: Does the title mention all involved parties?
questions.explanation: Does the title of the article include everyone who was involved in the crash?

questions.text: Does the headline mention all involved parties?

questions.explanation: Does the headline mention all involved parties using a human word (e.g. 'pedestrian'; 'driver'), NOT using names of transportation modes (e.g. 'car', 'motorbike')?

questions.text: ... and the sentence is written in active grammar?
questions.explanation: Active instead of passive grammar, for example: 'Driver hits cyclist' (active) instead of 'Cyclist hit by driver' (passive).

questions.text: And the full article mentions specific physical and/or psychological consequences for all involved parties?
questions.explanation: Generic expressions such as 'injured', 'damage' or 'taken to hospital' are not specific enough.

questions.text: ... and the full article places the crash in a larger pattern of crashes?
questions.explanation: A pattern can be about the location of the crash or the general number of crashes (local, national, global, etc.).

questions.text: ... and the subject of the sentence is also human?

questions.explanation: An article that highlights and focuses on not the crash itself, but an event that followed, such as a lawsuit.
